# Ways of Working: {{ display_name }}

## Definition of Done

A feature is considered done when:

- [ ] Code is written and passes all lint checks
- [ ] Tests are written and passing (matching the {{ test_strategy }} strategy)
- [ ] Documentation is updated if the change affects architecture or APIs
- [ ] Code has been reviewed by at least one team member
- [ ] Feature is deployed to a staging/preview environment
- [ ] Acceptance criteria from the ticket are met

## Branching Strategy

We use **trunk-based development** with short-lived feature branches.

### Branch Naming

```
feature/<ticket-id>-<short-description>
fix/<ticket-id>-<short-description>
chore/<description>
docs/<description>
```

### Workflow

1. Create a branch from `main`
2. Make small, focused commits
3. Open a Pull Request early (draft if WIP)
4. Request review when ready
5. Squash-merge into `main`
6. Delete the branch after merge

## Pull Request Conventions

### PR Title

Use conventional commit format:

```
feat(dashboard): add widget drag-and-drop
fix(auth): resolve token refresh race condition
docs(architecture): update deployment diagram
```

### PR Description

Every PR should include:

- **What**: brief summary of changes
- **Why**: motivation or ticket reference
- **How**: implementation approach (if non-obvious)
- **Testing**: how the change was verified

### Review Expectations

- Review within 1 business day
- Focus on correctness, clarity, and maintainability
- Approve with minor comments rather than blocking on style

## Architecture Decision Records (ADRs)

We document significant architectural decisions in `docs/adrs/`.

### When to Write an ADR

- Introducing a new library or framework
- Changing the data model significantly
- Choosing between multiple valid approaches
- Establishing a new pattern or convention

### ADR Format

```markdown
# ADR-NNNN: Title

## Status
Proposed | Accepted | Deprecated | Superseded

## Context
What is the problem or situation?

## Decision
What did we decide?

## Consequences
What are the trade-offs?
```

## Testing Expectations

Strategy: **{{ test_strategy }}**

{% if test_strategy == "unit-and-integration" %}
- Every module with business logic has unit tests
- API endpoints have integration tests with a real database
- Critical UI components have component tests
- Aim for >80% coverage on business logic
{% elif test_strategy == "e2e-focused" %}
- Every user journey has an end-to-end test
- API endpoints have smoke tests
- Critical pages have visual regression tests
- Coverage targets focus on journey completion, not lines
{% elif test_strategy == "full-pyramid" %}
- Unit tests: all pure functions and business logic
- Integration tests: all API endpoints and service interactions
- E2E tests: top 10 user journeys
- Target: >80% unit coverage, >60% integration coverage
{% endif %}

### Test Naming

```
test_<unit>_<scenario>_<expected_result>
```

Example: `test_login_with_expired_token_returns_401`

## Documentation Expectations

- README: always up to date with setup instructions
- Architecture: update when structure changes
- ADRs: write for every significant decision
- API: document endpoints (OpenAPI or inline)
- Page templates: reference when building new pages

## AI Collaboration Guidelines

{% if ai_context %}
This project is designed for AI-assisted development.

### For AI Agents

- Read `AI_CONTEXT.md` before starting work
- Follow the patterns described in architecture docs
- Reference page templates when building UI
- Write tests matching the project's testing strategy
- Create ADRs when introducing new patterns

### For Developers Working with AI

- Provide clear, scoped instructions
- Reference specific files and patterns
- Review AI-generated code against the same PR standards
- Update AI_CONTEXT.md when patterns change
{% else %}
When using AI coding assistants:

- Provide project context and conventions
- Review generated code thoroughly
- Ensure tests are included
- Update documentation for AI-introduced patterns
{% endif %}

## Communication

- Prefer async communication (comments, PRs, docs) over sync
- Document decisions, not just discussions
- Use the ADR process for architectural choices
